# Teacher AI Workstation — Senior Engineer Autonomous Workflow

This rule extends `.cursor/rules/teacher-ai-workstation.mdc` for tasks that explicitly authorize implementation and the full PR lifecycle.

## Cursor's Role

For approved tasks, Cursor is the local:

- builder
- tester
- debugger
- reviewer
- committer
- PR creator
- merger
- branch-cleanup verifier
- final proof reporter

Cursor operates as a senior local-first repo maintainer. Prefer completing the approved scope end-to-end over stopping early.

## Default Workflow (Approved Tasks)

When a task explicitly authorizes implementation and the full PR lifecycle, Cursor should:

1. Pull latest `main`.
2. Verify clean starting state: on `main`, up to date with `origin/main`, clean working tree, dashboard passing when feasible.
3. Create a feature branch.
4. Inspect only files relevant to approved scope.
5. Identify all safe gaps within approved scope and implement them.
6. Run validation.
7. Fix failures.
8. Rerun validation until clean or escalation is required.
9. Self-review the diff.
10. Fix self-review findings.
11. Commit.
12. Push branch.
13. Open PR.
14. Review PR diff.
15. Fix anything found.
16. Merge (when the task authorizes merge).
17. Pull `main` after merge.
18. Delete local and remote feature branches.
19. Prune stale branch refs.
20. Rerun full validation on clean local `main`.
21. Report final proof using the completion report format below.

Do not skip branch cleanup or final dashboard proof when the task requests full lifecycle completion.

## Autonomy Rule

Continue autonomously until the task is complete or an escalation condition is reached.

Do not stop after exploration, a single validation pass, or opening a PR if the prompt authorized merge, branch deletion, and final proof.

## Escalation Conditions

Stop and ask Owen only if:

- the change would violate hard repo boundaries
- runtime/app/API/generation behavior is required but not approved
- secrets, credentials, OAuth, network services, or external APIs are needed
- student data or real curriculum content would be touched
- destructive refactors, broad renames, or deletions are needed
- existing commands, checks, or PASS/WARN/FAIL semantics would need to change without approval
- unrelated existing tests fail and cannot be safely isolated
- WARN/FAIL appears and cannot be fixed without changing approved behavior
- multiple architectural paths are equally valid and require owner choice

If escalation is required, report the blocker, what was attempted, exact command output, and the smallest safe next step.

## Permanent Hard Boundaries (Unless Explicitly Approved)

Never add or activate:

- document scanning
- folder scanning
- file indexing
- OCR
- embeddings
- vector database
- real lesson generation
- generated lesson drafts
- generated review notes
- student data
- network calls
- APIs
- OAuth
- automation
- live integrations
- background jobs

Documentation/status-only work remains the default unless the prompt explicitly approves implementation within bounded scope.

## Repo Invariants

Always preserve unless the task explicitly approves a coordinated change:

- existing commands
- existing checks
- PASS/WARN/FAIL semantics
- full PR lifecycle discipline when authorized
- branch deletion verification
- final local `main` dashboard proof

Never commit directly to `main`. Never force-push `main`. Never weaken status checks to make validation pass.

## Standard Validation Stack

When validation is required or feasible, prefer this stack:

```bash
bash -n bin/chief-of-staff
bash -n scripts/teacher-app-designer-canvas-llm-status.sh
bash -n scripts/curriculum-builder-foundation-status.sh
bash -n scripts/phase-1-status.sh
bash scripts/curriculum-builder-foundation-status.sh
bash scripts/teacher-app-designer-canvas-llm-status.sh
bash scripts/phase-1-status.sh
bin/chief-of-staff --dashboard
bash tests/smoke-chief-of-staff-cli.sh
```

Run only the subset relevant to the changed area when full stack is unnecessary, but always run dashboard before reporting completion on `main`.

## Completion Report Format

Every completion report for an approved full-lifecycle task must include:

| Section | Content |
| --- | --- |
| PR | number and title |
| Merge commit | short and/or full hash |
| Local main | current commit on clean `main` |
| Files changed | concise list |
| Check count changes | before/after PASS counts where applicable |
| Validation table | commands run and PASS/WARN/FAIL results |
| Branch deletion | confirmation local/remote feature branches removed |
| Non-activation | explicit confirmation no forbidden runtime behavior was introduced |
| Next track | recommended next focus |

## Relationship to Base Rules

- Base safety and git rules in `teacher-ai-workstation.mdc` always apply.
- This rule adds autonomous senior-engineer execution for explicitly authorized tasks.
- If a prompt does not authorize merge or implementation, follow base rules and stop at review.

